\subsection*{Why am I here?}
I have analyses that I have done based on somewhat ad hoc theory, where I
am comfortable that I have done good science but would appreciate confirmation
of the underlying method. I have other, pending analyses where things are
still foggy. I bring real data (which you can use) and real problems, and
you all can supply the answers. 

A second issue will be coding.  I have made several choices wrt multistate
models in the survival package, and in the new mshmm package.  Are they
sensible, useful, understandable, \ldots?

More importantly, this will give us a chance to talk about issues that arise
in real data, which I hope will be useful. 

\section{Semi-theory}
The three most popular models in statistics are
\begin{itemize}
   \item Linear: $E(y) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \ldots$
   \item GLM: $E(y) = g\left(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \ldots \right)$
   \item Cox: $\lambda(t) = g\left(\beta_0(t) + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \ldots \right)$
\end{itemize}

The reason why is simplicity.
If `x1= apoepos`, then $\beta_1$ is *THE* effect of APOE, independent of any other variables in the model.
Statisticians like this.
Investigators really like this (a simple story).
Regulators demand it --- a single yes/no p-value.

\begin{itemize}
  \item Generalized additive models will replace one of the $\beta x$ terms
      with $s(x)$, but retain the separability.
  \item The function $g$ is chosen to make the model code never fail, which
    means never predicting an impossible value.
    \begin{itemize}
      \item binomial: logistic, probit, cloglog
      \item Cox, poisson: exp
    \end{itemize}
  \item The makes the models less interpretable.      
\end{itemize}

Science is not always this simple, and multi-state models break the rules.
That is, a description of the final fit can not be boiled down to one
number.  

\section{Examples}
Many of these will be further explained in the draft book (Atkinson, Crowson
and Therneau) and its examples.  These are part of the materials for the
course.  Some data sets are in the survival package, some in the mshmm package
(github.com/therneau/mshmm).

\subsection{Crohn's disease}
This is discussed in the Therneau and Grambsh (2000), before I understood
multistate models very well.  The data has been made available in the
mshmm package.  I would be very interested in a more thoughtful analysis.
  
Crohn's disease is a chronic idopathic disease of the gut
 characterized by transmural inflammation and ulceration.  Managment
 may require immunosuppressive drugs and surgical interventions.
This data follows an inception cohort of 174 residents from 1970
through 1993, with a median follow-up of 10 years. 
The waxing and waning nature of the disease makes it challenging to
analyse. 
\begin{itemize}
  \item 1488 observations on 174 subjects
  \item States of remission, mild, treatment responsive, treament dependent,
    treatment resistant, surgery, death
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Fatty liver disease}
Data from a cohort of subjectsw with non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)
and a set of matched controls. 
Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) was renamed metabolic
dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) in 1993;
the new name is intended to better reflect the disease's underlying causes,
identify subgroups of patients, and avoid stigmatizing words.

The study constructed a population cohort of all MASLD subjects from 1997 to 
2014 along with 4 potential controls for each case, matched on age, sex, and
calendar year.  The primary analysis looked at the incidence of 3 metabolic
comorbidities of diabetes, hypertension, and dyslipidemia.
See chapter 12 of the book

