\section{Data}
The survival package accepts two kinds of input data: counting
process and timeline style.  The mshmm and msm packages require
timeline style.

<<counting>>=
pdat0 <- subset(pbcseq, !duplicated(id))
pdat0$age10 <- pdat0$age/10
pdat0$bili3 <- cut(pdat0$bili, c(0,1,5,100), c("normal", "1-4", ">4"))
pdat0$death <- 1*(pdat0$status ==2)

# Create the time1, time2 dataset
pdata <- tmerge(pdat0[,c(1,4:6)], pdat0, id=id,
                 death = event(futime, death),
                 options= list(tstart="day1", tstop="day2"))

# I have arbitrarily decided not to make use of any new lab within 7
#  days of death.  This loses 33 bilirubin values.
ptemp <- subset(pbcseq, !(status ==2 & (futime <= (day + 7))))
ptemp$bili3 <- cut(ptemp$bili, c(0, 1, 4, 100), c("normal", "1-4", ">4"))
ptemp$agrp  <- cut(-ptemp$albumin, c(-100, -3.5, -3, 0),
                   c("normal", "3-3.5", "<3"))
pdata <- tmerge(pdata, ptemp, id=id, edema = tdc(day, edema),
                bili= tdc(day, bili), albumin = tdc(day, albumin),
                protime = tdc(day, protime),
                bili3 = tdc(day, bili3), b3= event(day, as.numeric(bili3)),
                agrp  = tdc(day, agrp))

subset(pdata, id<3, c(id, trt, sex, edema, bili, day1, day2, death))
@

\begin{itemize}
 \item For this subject: id
 \item Over this interval: (day1, day2]
 \item These are the covariates: trt, sex, edema, bili
 \item The interval ends with alive/dead transition: death
\end{itemize}

<<counting2>>= 
# Now create the multistate dataset using bilirubin groups
# 1. By definition, bilirubin can only change on 'pbcseq' days
# 2. Don't count two visits in the same state as a transition
temp <- with(pdata, ifelse(death, 4,
                           ifelse(as.numeric(bili3)==b3, 0, b3)))
pdata$bstate <- factor(temp, 0:4, c("none", "normal", "1-4", ">4", "death"))
pdata$year1 <- pdata$day1/365.25
pdata$year2 <- pdata$day2/365.25

survcheck(Surv(year1, year2, bstate) ~ 1, pdata, id=id, istate=bili3)
@ 

Timeline data
\begin{itemize}
  \item Subject id and time
  \item Covariates and/or status observed at that time
  \item Potentially lots of missing values
  \item Simple survival: 2 rows per subject
\end{itemize}

<<timeline>>=
pdata2 <- subset(pbcseq, select= -c(hepato, spiders, chol, alk.phos, ast,
                                    platelet, futime, status))
pdata2$death <- 0
pdata2$bili3 <- cut(pdata2$bili, c(0, 1, 4, 100), levels(pdata$bili3))

temp <- subset(pbcseq, !duplicated(id), c(id, futime, status))
temp$day <- temp$futime
temp$death <- 1*(temp$status==2)

pdata2 <- merge(pdata2, temp, all=TRUE)

temp <- with(pdata2, ifelse(!duplicated(id, fromLast=TRUE), 4*death,
                            as.numeric(bili3)))
pdata2$bstate <- factor(temp, 0:4,  
                        c("none", "normal", "1-4", ">4", "death"))
subset(pdata2, id <3, c(id, day, death, bstate, trt, age, sex, protime))

survcheck(Surv2(day, bstate) ~ 1, pdata2, id=id)

survcheck(Surv2(as.numeric(day), bstate) ~ 1, pdata2, id=id)
@

Timeline data sets are easier to create, and I suspect that timeline 
form will become ascendant.

What about missing values?  Say that someone has a row, in the middle of
follow-up, with a missing bilirubin.  If that row is removed survcheck will
fail, and it should.

What if we have a 3 state model, and the covariate e4pos is part of the
model for ND:dementia but not for ND:death or dementia:death. Should subjects
who are missing e4 be used for part of the model and not others?

